# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: source-maps
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:source-maps/debugging] In engineering, **debugging** is the process of finding the root cause, workarounds, and possible fixes for bugs.
[src:source-maps/debugging] For software, debugging tactics can involve interactive debugging, control flow analysis, log file analysis, monitoring at the application or system level, memory dumps, and profiling.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Many programming languages and software development tools also offer programs to aid in debugging, known as debuggers.
[src:source-maps/debugging] The term *bug*, in the sense of defect, dates back at least to 1878 when Thomas Edison wrote "little faults and difficulties" in his inventions as "Bugs".
[src:source-maps/debugging] A popular story from the 1940's is from Admiral Grace Hopper.
[src:source-maps/debugging] While she was working on a Mark II computer at Harvard University, her associates discovered a moth stuck in a relay that impeded operation and wrote in a log book "First actual case of a bug being found".
[src:source-maps/debugging] Although probably a joke, conflating the two meanings of bug (biological and defect), the story indicates that the term was used in the computer field at that time.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Similarly, the term *debugging* was used in aeronautics before entering the world of computers.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Robert Oppenheimer, director of the WWII atomic bomb Manhattan Project at Los Alamos, used the term in a letter to Dr.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Ernest Lawrence at UC Berkeley, dated October 27, 1944, regarding the recruitment of additional technical staff.
[src:source-maps/debugging] The Oxford English Dictionary entry for *debug* uses the term *debugging* in reference to airplane engine testing in a 1945 article in the Journal of the Royal Aeronautical Society.
[src:source-maps/debugging] 50) refers to *debugging* aircraft cameras.
[src:source-maps/debugging] The seminal article by Gill in 1951 is the earliest in-depth discussion of programming errors, but it does not use the term *bug* or *debugging*.
[src:source-maps/debugging] In the ACM's digital library, the term *debugging* is first used in three papers from the 1952 ACM National Meetings.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Two of the three use the term in quotation marks.
[src:source-maps/debugging] By 1963, *debugging* was a common enough term to be mentioned in passing without explanation on page 1 of the CTSS manual.
[src:source-maps/debugging] As software and electronic systems have become generally more complex, the various common debugging techniques have expanded with more methods to detect anomalies, assess impact, and schedule software patches or full updates to a system.
[src:source-maps/debugging] The words "anomaly" and "discrepancy" can be used, as being more neutral terms, to avoid the words "error" and "defect" or "bug" where there might be an implication that all so-called *errors*, *defects* or *bugs* must be fixed (at all costs).
[src:source-maps/debugging] Instead, an impact assessment can be made to determine if changes to remove an *anomaly* (or *discrepancy*) would be cost-effective for the system, or perhaps a scheduled new release might render the change(s) unnecessary.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Not all issues are safety-critical or mission-critical in a system.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Also, it is important to avoid the situation where a change might be more upsetting to users, long-term, than living with the known problem(s) (where the "cure would be worse than the disease").
[src:source-maps/debugging] Basing decisions of the acceptability of some anomalies can avoid a culture of a "zero-defects" mandate, where people might be tempted to deny the existence of problems so that the result would appear as zero *defects*.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Considering the collateral issues, such as the cost-versus-benefit impact assessment, then broader debugging techniques will expand to determine the frequency of anomalies (how often the same "bugs" occur) to help assess their impact to the overall system.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Debugging ranges in complexity from fixing simple errors to performing lengthy and tiresome tasks of data collection, analysis, and scheduling updates.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Debuggers are software tools which enable the programmer to monitor the execution of a program, stop it, restart it, set breakpoints, and change values in memory.
[src:source-maps/debugging] The term *debugger* can also refer to the person who is doing the debugging.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Generally, high-level programming languages, such as Java, make debugging easier, because they have features such as exception handling and type checking that make real sources of erratic behaviour easier to spot.
[src:source-maps/debugging] In programming languages such as C or assembly, bugs may cause silent problems such as memory corruption, and it is often difficult to see where the initial problem happened.
[src:source-maps/debugging] In those cases, memory debugger tools may be needed.
[src:source-maps/debugging] In certain situations, general purpose software tools that are language specific in nature can be very useful.
[src:source-maps/debugging] These take the form of *static code analysis tools*.
[src:source-maps/debugging] These tools look for a very specific set of known problems, some common and some rare, within the source code, concentrating more on the semantics (e.g. data flow) rather than the syntax, as compilers and interpreters do.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Both commercial and free tools exist for various languages; some claim to be able to detect hundreds of different problems.
[src:source-maps/debugging] These tools can be extremely useful when checking very large source trees, where it is impractical to do code walk-throughs.
[src:source-maps/debugging] A typical example of a problem detected would be a variable dereference that occurs *before* the variable is assigned a value.
[src:source-maps/debugging] As another example, some such tools perform strong type checking when the language does not require it.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Thus, they are better at locating likely errors in code that is syntactically correct.
[src:source-maps/debugging] But these tools have a reputation of false positives, where correct code is flagged as dubious.
[src:source-maps/debugging] The old Unix *lint* program is an early example.
[src:source-maps/debugging] For debugging electronic hardware (e.g., computer hardware) as well as low-level software (e.g., BIOSes, device drivers) and firmware, instruments such as oscilloscopes, logic analyzers, or in-circuit emulators (ICEs) are often used, alone or in combination.
[src:source-maps/debugging] An ICE may perform many of the typical software debugger's tasks on low-level software and firmware.
[src:source-maps/debugging] The debugging process normally begins with identifying the steps to reproduce the problem.
[src:source-maps/debugging] This can be a non-trivial task, particularly with parallel processes and some Heisenbugs for example.
[src:source-maps/debugging] The specific user environment and usage history can also make it difficult to reproduce the problem.
[src:source-maps/debugging] After the bug is reproduced, the input of the program may need to be simplified to make it easier to debug.
[src:source-maps/debugging] For example, a bug in a compiler can make it crash when parsing a large source file.
[src:source-maps/debugging] However, after simplification of the test case, only few lines from the original source file can be sufficient to reproduce the same crash.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Simplification may be done manually using a divide-and-conquer approach, in which the programmer attempts to remove some parts of original test case then checks if the problem still occurs.
[src:source-maps/debugging] When debugging in a GUI, the programmer can try skipping some user interaction from the original problem description to check if the remaining actions are sufficient for causing the bug to occur.
[src:source-maps/debugging] After the test case is sufficiently simplified, a programmer can use a debugger tool to examine program states (values of variables, plus the call stack) and track down the origin of the problem(s).
[src:source-maps/debugging] In simple cases, tracing is just a few print statements which output the values of variables at particular points during the execution of the program.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Automatic bug-fixing is the automatic repair of software bugs without the intervention of a human programmer.
[src:source-maps/debugging] It is also commonly referred to as *automatic patch generation*, *automatic bug repair*, or *automatic program repair*.
[src:source-maps/debugging] The typical goal of such techniques is to automatically generate correct patches to eliminate bugs in software programs without causing software regression.
[src:source-maps/debugging] In contrast to the general purpose computer software design environment, a primary characteristic of embedded environments is the sheer number of different platforms available to the developers (CPU architectures, vendors, operating systems, and their variants).
[src:source-maps/debugging] Embedded systems are, by definition, not general-purpose designs: they are typically developed for a single task (or small range of tasks), and the platform is chosen specifically to optimize that application.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Not only does this fact make life tough for embedded system developers, it also makes debugging and testing of these systems harder as well, since different debugging tools are needed for different platforms.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Despite the challenge of heterogeneity mentioned above, some debuggers have been developed commercially as well as research prototypes.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Examples of commercial solutions come from Green Hills Software, Lauterbach GmbH and Microchip's MPLAB-ICD (for in-circuit debugger).
[src:source-maps/debugging] Two examples of research prototype tools are Aveksha and Flocklab.
[src:source-maps/debugging] They all leverage a functionality available on low-cost embedded processors, an On-Chip Debug Module (OCDM), whose signals are exposed through a standard JTAG interface.
[src:source-maps/debugging] They are benchmarked based on how much change to the application is needed and the rate of events that they can keep up with.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Anti-debugging is "the implementation of one or more techniques within computer code that hinders attempts at reverse engineering or debugging a target process".
[src:source-maps/debugging] It is actively used by recognized publishers in copy-protection schemas, but is also used by malware to complicate its detection and elimination.
[src:source-maps/debugging] An early example of anti-debugging existed in early versions of Microsoft Word which, if a debugger was detected, produced a message that said, "The tree of evil bears bitter fruit.
[src:source-maps/debugging] Now trashing program disk.", after which it caused the floppy disk drive to emit alarming noises with the intent of scaring the user away from attempting it again.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:source-maps/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:source-maps/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:source-maps/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:source-maps/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:source-maps/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:source-maps/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:source-maps/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:source-maps/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:source-maps/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:source-maps/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:source-maps/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:source-maps/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:source-maps/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:source-maps/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:source-maps/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:source-maps/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:source-maps/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:source-maps/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:source-maps/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:source-maps/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:source-maps/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:source-maps/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:source-maps/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:source-maps/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:source-maps/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:source-maps/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:source-maps/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:source-maps/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:source-maps/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:source-maps/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:source-maps/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:source-maps/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:source-maps/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:source-maps/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:source-maps/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:source-maps/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:source-maps/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:source-maps/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:source-maps/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:source-maps/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:source-maps/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:source-maps/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:source-maps/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:source-maps/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:source-maps/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:source-maps/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:source-maps/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:source-maps/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:source-maps/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:source-maps/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:source-maps/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:source-maps/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:source-maps/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:source-maps/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:source-maps/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:source-maps/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:source-maps/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:source-maps/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:source-maps/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:source-maps/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:source-maps/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:source-maps/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:source-maps/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:source-maps/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:source-maps/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:source-maps/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:source-maps/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:source-maps/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:source-maps/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:source-maps/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:source-maps/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:source-maps/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:source-maps/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:source-maps/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:source-maps/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:source-maps/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:source-maps/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:source-maps/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:source-maps/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:source-maps/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:source-maps/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:source-maps/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:source-maps/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:source-maps/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:source-maps/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:source-maps/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:source-maps/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:source-maps/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:source-maps/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:source-maps/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:source-maps/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:source-maps/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] Minification can be distinguished from the more general concept of data compression in that the minified source can be interpreted immediately without the need for a decompression step: the same interpreter can work with both the original as well as with the minified source.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] The goals of minification are not the same as the goals of obfuscation; the former is often intended to be reversed using a pretty printer or unminifier.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] However, to achieve its goals, minification sometimes uses techniques also used by obfuscation; for example, shortening variable names and refactoring the source code.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] When minification uses such techniques, the pretty-printer or unminifier can only fully reverse the minification process if it is supplied details of the transformations done by such techniques.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] If not supplied those details, the reversed source code will contain different variable names and control flow, even though it will have the same functionality as the original source code.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] In 2001 Douglas Crockford introduced JSMin, which removed comments and whitespace from JavaScript code.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] It was followed by YUI Compressor in 2007.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] In 2009, Google opened up its Closure toolkit, including Closure Compiler which contained a source mapping feature together with a Firefox extension called Closure Inspector.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] In 2010, Mihai Bazon introduced UglifyJS, which was superseded by UglifyJS2 in 2012; the rewrite was to allow for source map support.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] From 2017, Alex Lam took over maintenance and development of UglifyJS2, replacing it with UglifyJS3 which unified the CLI with the API.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] In 2018, Terser has been forked from uglify-es and has gained momentum since; in 2020 it outstripped UglifyJS when measured in daily downloads.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] Since late 2018, Terser has recommended the bundler RollupJS.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] A **source map** is a file format that allows software tools for JavaScript to display different code to a user than the code actually executed by the computer.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] For example, to aid in debugging of minified code, by "mapping" this code to the original unminified source code instead.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] The original format was created by Joseph Schorr as part of the Closure Inspector minification project.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] Version 2 and 3 of the format reduced the size of the map files considerably.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] In 2024, source maps were standardized by Ecma International's TC39 technical committee as ECMA-426.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] JavaScript and Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) resources may be minified, preserving their behavior while considerably reducing their file size.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] Libraries available online are capable of minification and optimization to varying degrees.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] Some libraries also merge multiple script files into a single file for client download.
[src:source-maps/minification-programming] JavaScript source maps can make code readable and debuggable even after it has been combined and minified.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] A source-to-source translator converts between programming languages that operate at approximately the same level of abstraction, while a traditional compiler translates from a higher level language to a lower level language.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] For example, a source-to-source translator may perform a translation of a program from Python to JavaScript, while a traditional compiler translates from a language like C to assembly or Java to bytecode.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] An automatic parallelizing compiler will frequently take in a high level language program as an input and then transform the code and annotate it with parallel code annotations (e.g., OpenMP) or language constructs (e.g.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Another purpose of source-to-source-compiling is translating legacy code to use the next version of the underlying programming language or an application programming interface (API) that breaks backward compatibility.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Transcompilers may either keep translated code structure as close to the source code as possible to ease development and debugging of the original source code or may change the structure of the original code so much that the translated code does not look like the source code.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Examples include Closure Compiler, CoffeeScript, Dart, Haxe, Opal, TypeScript and Emscripten.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] So called *Assembly language translators* are a class of source-to-source translators converting code from one assembly language into another, including (but not limited to) across different processor families and system platforms.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Intel marketed their 16-bit processor 8086 to be source compatible to the 8080, an 8-bit processor.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] To support this, Intel had an ISIS-II-based translator from 8080 to 8086 source code named CONV86 (also referred to as CONV-86 and CONVERT 86) available to OEM customers since 1978, possibly the earliest program of this kind.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] It supported multiple levels of translation and ran at 2 MHz on an Intel Microprocessor Development System MDS-800 with 8-inch floppy drives.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] According to user reports, it did not work very reliably.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Seattle Computer Products (SCP) offered TRANS86.COM, written by Tim Paterson in 1980 while developing 86-DOS.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Also, performing only a mere transliteration, the brute-force single-pass translator did not carry out any register and jump optimizations.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] The SCP version 1 of TRANS86.COM ran on Z80-based systems.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Once 86-DOS was running, Paterson, in a self-hosting-inspired approach, utilized TRANS86 to convert itself into a program running under 86-DOS.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Numbered version 2, this was named TRANS.COM instead.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Later in 1982, the translator was apparently also available from Microsoft.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Also named TRANS86, Sorcim offered an 8080 to 8086 translator as well since December 1980.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Like SCP's program it was designed to port CP/M-80 application code (in ASM, MAC, RMAC or ACT80 assembly format) to MS-DOS (in a format compatible with ACT86).
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] In ACT80 format it also supported a few Z80 mnemonics.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] The translation occurred on an instruction-by-instruction basis with some optimization applied to conditional jumps.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] The program ran under CP/M-80, MP/M-80 and Cromemco DOS with a minimum of 24 KB of RAM, and had no restrictions on the source file size.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Much more sophisticated and the first to introduce optimizing compiler technologies into the source translation process was Digital Research's XLT86 1.0 in September 1981.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] The program was written by Gary Kildall and translated .ASM source code for the Intel 8080 processor (in a format compatible with ASM, MAC or RMAC assemblers) into .A86 source code for the 8086 (compatible with ASM86).
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] XLT86.COM itself was written in PL/I-80 for CP/M-80 platforms.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] The program occupied 30 KB of RAM for itself plus additional memory for the program graph.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] On a 64 KB memory system, the maximum source file size supported was about 6 KB, so that larger files had to be broken down accordingly before translation.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Alternatively, XLT86 was also available for DEC VAX/VMS.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Although XLT86's input and output worked on source-code level, the translator's in-memory representation of the program and the applied code optimizing technologies set the foundation to binary recompilation.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] 2500 AD Software offered an 8080 to 8086 source-code translator as part of their XASM suite for CP/M-80 machines with Z80 as well as for Zilog ZEUS and Olivetti PCOS systems.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Since 1979, Zilog offered a Z80 to Z8000 translator as part of their PDS 8000 development system.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Advanced Micro Computers (AMC) and 2500 AD Software offered Z80 to Z8000 translators as well.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] The latter was named TRANS and was available for Z80 CP/M, CP/M-86, MS-DOS and PCOS.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] The Z88DK development kit provides a Z80 to i486 source code translator targeting nasm named "to86.awk", written in 2008 by Stefano Bodrato.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] It is in turn based on an 8080 to Z80 converter written in 2003 by Douglas Beattie, Jr., named "toz80.awk".
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] In 2021, Brian Callahan wrote an 8080 CP/M 2.2 to MS-DOS source code translator targeting nasm named 8088ify.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] The first implementations of some programming languages started as transcompilers, and the default implementation for some of those languages are still transcompilers.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] In addition to the table below, a CoffeeScript maintainer provides a list of languages that compile to JavaScript.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] When developers want to switch to a different language while retaining most of an existing codebase, it might be better to use a transcompiler compared to rewriting the whole software by hand.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Depending on the quality of the transcompiler, the code may or may not need manual intervention in order to work properly.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] This is different from "transcompiled languages" where the specifications demand that the output source code always works without modification.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] All transcompilers used to port a codebase will expect manual adjustment of the output source code if there is a need to achieve maximum code quality in terms of readability and platform convention.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] A transcompiler pipeline is what results from *recursive transcompiling*.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] By stringing together multiple layers of tech, with a transcompile step between each layer, technology can be repeatedly transformed, effectively creating a distributed language independent specification.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] XSLT is a general-purpose transform tool that can be used between many different technologies, to create such a derivative code pipeline.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] By repeating this process, one can turn A → B → C → D → E → F and then back into A(v2).
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] Some information will be preserved through this pipeline, from A → A(v2), and that information (at an abstract level) demonstrates what each of the components A–F agree on.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] In each of the different versions that the transcompiler pipeline produces, that information is preserved.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] It might take on many different shapes and sizes, but by the time it comes back to A (v2), having been transcompiled six times in the pipeline above, the information returns to its original state.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] This information which survives the transform through each format, from A–F–A(v2), is (by definition) derivative content or derivative code.
[src:source-maps/source-to-source-compiler] There are also debugging utilities that map the transcompiled source code back to the original code; for example, JavaScript source maps allow mapping of the JavaScript code executed by a web browser back to the original source in a transcompiled-to-JavaScript language.
[src:source-maps/typescript] TypeScript may be used to develop JavaScript applications for both client-side and server-side execution (as with React.js, Node.js, Deno or Bun).
[src:source-maps/typescript] Multiple options are available for transpiling.
[src:source-maps/typescript] The default TypeScript Compiler can be used, or the Babel compiler can be invoked to convert TypeScript to JavaScript.
[src:source-maps/typescript] TypeScript supports definition files that can contain type information of existing JavaScript libraries, much like C++ header files can describe the structure of existing object files.
[src:source-maps/typescript] This enables other programs to use the values defined in the files as if they were statically typed TypeScript entities.
[src:source-maps/typescript] There are third-party header files for popular libraries such as jQuery, MongoDB, and D3.js.
[src:source-maps/typescript] TypeScript headers for the Node.js library modules are also available, allowing development of Node.js programs within TypeScript.
[src:source-maps/typescript] The TypeScript compiler is written in TypeScript and compiled to JavaScript.
[src:source-maps/typescript] It is licensed under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:source-maps/typescript] Anders Hejlsberg, lead architect of C# and creator of Delphi and Turbo Pascal, has worked on developing TypeScript.
[src:source-maps/typescript] TypeScript was released to the public in October 2012, with version 0.8, after two years of internal development at Microsoft.
[src:source-maps/typescript] Soon after the initial public release, Miguel de Icaza praised the language, but criticized the lack of mature integrated development environment (IDE) support apart from Microsoft Visual Studio, which was unavailable then on Linux and macOS.
[src:source-maps/typescript] As of April 2021 there is support in other IDEs and text editors, including Emacs, Vim, WebStorm, Atom and Microsoft's own Visual Studio Code.
[src:source-maps/typescript] TypeScript 0.9, released in 2013, added support for generics.
[src:source-maps/typescript] TypeScript 1.0 was released at Microsoft's Build developer conference in 2014.
[src:source-maps/typescript] Visual Studio 2013 Update 2 provided built-in support for TypeScript.
[src:source-maps/typescript] Further improvement were made in July 2014, when the development team announced a new TypeScript compiler, asserted to have a five-fold performance increase.
[src:source-maps/typescript] Simultaneously, the source code, which was initially hosted on CodePlex, was moved to GitHub.
[src:source-maps/typescript] On 22 September 2016, TypeScript 2.0 was released, introducing several features, including the ability for programmers to optionally enforce null safety.
[src:source-maps/typescript] TypeScript 3.0 was released on 30 July 2018, bringing many language additions like tuples in rest parameters and spread expressions, rest parameters with tuple types, generic rest parameters and so on.
[src:source-maps/typescript] TypeScript 4.0 was released on 20 August 2020.
[src:source-maps/typescript] While 4.0 did not introduce any breaking changes, it added language features such as Custom JSX Factories and Variadic Tuple Types.
[src:source-maps/typescript] TypeScript 5.0 was released on 16 March 2023 and included support for decorators.
[src:source-maps/typescript] On March 11, 2025, Anders Hejlsberg announced on the TypeScript blog that the team is working on a Go port of the TypeScript compiler to be released as TypeScript version 7.0 later this year.
[src:source-maps/typescript] It is expected to feature a 10x speedup.
[src:source-maps/typescript] On December 2nd, 2025, Daniel Rosenwasser announced on the blog that TypeScript 6.0 will be the last release written in TypeScript itself, and TypeScript 7.0 will be the first Go-based release.
[src:source-maps/typescript] TypeScript originated from the shortcomings of JavaScript for developing large-scale applications both at Microsoft and among their external customers.
[src:source-maps/typescript] Challenges with dealing with complex JavaScript code led to demand for custom tooling to ease developing of components in the language.
[src:source-maps/typescript] Developers sought a solution that would not break compatibility with the ECMAScript (ES) standard and its ecosystem, so a compiler was developed to transform a superset of JavaScript with type annotations and classes (TypeScript files) back into vanilla ECMAScript 5 code.
[src:source-maps/typescript] TypeScript classes were based on the then-proposed ECMAScript 6 class specification to make writing prototypal inheritance less verbose and error-prone, and type annotations enabled IntelliSense and improved tooling.
[src:source-maps/typescript] Syntactically, TypeScript is very similar to JScript .NET, another Microsoft implementation of the ECMA-262 language standard that added support for static typing and classical object-oriented language features such as classes, inheritance, interfaces, and namespaces.
[src:source-maps/typescript] As TypeScript is simply a superset of JavaScript, existing JavaScript can be adapted to TypeScript and TypeScript program can seamlessly consume JavaScript.
[src:source-maps/typescript] The compiler can target all ECMAScript versions 5 and above, transpiling modern features like classes and arrow functions to their older counterparts.
[src:source-maps/typescript] With TypeScript, it is possible to use existing JavaScript code, incorporate popular JavaScript libraries, and call TypeScript-generated code from other JavaScript.
[src:source-maps/typescript] Type declarations for these libraries are usually provided with the source code but can be declared or installed separately if needed.
[src:source-maps/typescript] The TypeScript compiler, named `tsc`, is written in TypeScript.
[src:source-maps/typescript] As a result, it can be compiled into regular JavaScript and can then be executed in any JavaScript engine (e.g. a browser).
[src:source-maps/typescript] The compiler package comes bundled with a script host that can execute the compiler.
[src:source-maps/typescript] It is also available as a Node.js package that uses Node.js as a host.
[src:source-maps/typescript] The compiler is currently being rewritten in Go for version 7.
[src:source-maps/typescript] The compiler can *target* a given edition of ECMAScript (such as ECMAScript 5 for legacy browser compatibility), but by default compiles for the latest standards.
[src:source-maps/typescript] Using plug-ins, TypeScript can be integrated with build automation tools, including Grunt (grunt-ts), Apache Maven (TypeScript Maven Plugin), Gulp (gulp-typescript) and Gradle (TypeScript Gradle Plugin).
[src:source-maps/typescript] TSLint scans TypeScript code for conformance to a set of standards and guidelines.
[src:source-maps/typescript] ESLint, a standard JavaScript linter, also provided some support for TypeScript via community plugins.
[src:source-maps/typescript] However, ESLint's inability to leverage TypeScript's language services precluded certain forms of semantic linting and program-wide analysis.
[src:source-maps/typescript] In early 2019, the TSLint team announced the linter's deprecation in favor of `typescript-eslint`, a joint effort of the TSLint, ESLint and TypeScript teams to consolidate linting under the ESLint umbrella for improved performance, community unity and developer accessibility.
